  {
    "comprehension": null,
    "direction": null,
    "content": "<p>Observe the following substances.</p>\n<p>Ethanol, acetic acid, ethylamine, trimethylamine, salicylic acid. ethanal.</p>\n<p>In the above list, the number of substances with H -bonding is</p>",
    "options": [
      {
        "identifier": "A",
        "content": "<p>4</p>\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "B",
        "content": "<p>3</p>\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "C",
        "content": "<p>5</p>\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": "<p>2</p>"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "A"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>Hydrogen bonding occurs when a molecule has a hydrogen atom bonded to a highly electronegative atom like <strong>N, O, or F</strong> — and there is a lone pair on another <strong>N, O, or F</strong> atom that can participate in bonding.</p>\n\n<h3>1. <strong>Ethanol (CH₃CH₂OH)</strong></h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Has an –OH group  </li>\n</ul>\n<p>✅ <strong>Can form hydrogen bonds</strong> (O–H···O)</p>\n\n<h3>2. <strong>Acetic acid (CH₃COOH)</strong></h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Has both C=O and –OH groups  </li>\n</ul>\n<p>✅ <strong>Forms strong hydrogen bonds</strong> (dimers, intramolecular and intermolecular H-bonding possible)</p>\n\n<h3>3. <strong>Ethylamine (CH₃CH₂NH₂)</strong></h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Has an –NH₂ group  </li>\n</ul>\n<p>✅ <strong>Can form hydrogen bonds</strong> (N–H···N or N–H···O with other molecules)</p>\n\n<h3>4. <strong>Trimethylamine ((CH₃)₃N)</strong></h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Has nitrogen with a lone pair but <strong>no N–H bond</strong>  </li>\n</ul>\n<p>❌ <strong>Cannot form H-bonds as donor</strong>, though it can accept them — but “having H‑bonding” typically means being capable of <em>intermolecular H-bonding</em> as both donor and acceptor. Since it cannot donate an H, we generally <strong>do not count it</strong> as hydrogen‑bonding on its own.</p>\n\n<h3>5. <strong>Salicylic acid (o-hydroxybenzoic acid)</strong></h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Has both –OH and –COOH groups; strong <strong>intramolecular</strong> hydrogen bond and intermolecular as well.  </li>\n</ul>\n<p>✅ <strong>H-bonding present</strong></p>\n\n<h3>6. <strong>Ethanal (CH₃CHO)</strong></h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Has a C=O group only, no –OH or –NH–  </li>\n</ul>\n<p>❌ <strong>Cannot form hydrogen bonds</strong> with itself (can accept H bonds but not donate).</p>\n\n<p>✅ Substances with H‑bonding:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><p>Ethanol  </p></li>\n<li><p>Acetic acid  </p></li>\n<li><p>Ethylamine  </p></li>\n<li><p>Salicylic acid  </p></li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Total = 4</strong></p>\n\n<p>✅ <strong>Correct Answer: Option A (4)</strong></p>",
    "topic": null,
    "year": 2025,
    "yearKey": "ap-eapcet-2025-24th-may-morning-shift",
    "difficulty": null
  },
  {
    "comprehension": null,
    "direction": null,
    "content": "<p>In compound $(X)$, hyperconjugation is present and in $(Y)$, resonance effect is present. What are $X$ and $Y$, respectively?</p>",
    "options": [
      {
        "identifier": "A",
        "content": "<p>Toluene, prop-2-en-1-ol</p>\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "B",
        "content": "<p>Aniline, 2-propenal</p>\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "C",
        "content": "<p>Toluene, nitrobenzene</p>\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": "<p>1-bromopropane, phenol</p>"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "C"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>Toluene would be a suitable example of $X$ and nitrobenzene for $Y$.</p>\n<p>In toluene, the methyl group CH bond can participate in hyperconjugation with the pi system of benzene ring.</p>\n<p>Nitrobenzene exhibit resonance due to the interaction of the lone pair on the oxygen atom of the nitrogroup with the pi electrons of the benzene ring.</p>",
    "topic": null,
    "year": 2025,
    "yearKey": "ap-eapcet-2025-24th-may-morning-shift",
    "difficulty": null
  },
