    "explanation": "<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1ly9ttyer/1819a272-1682-4ee5-ba38-6d5af8f6e0a6/b07a0c30-3b6c-11ef-9b9d-75eda371a206/file-jaoe38c1ly9ttyes.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1ly9ttyer/1819a272-1682-4ee5-ba38-6d5af8f6e0a6/b07a0c30-3b6c-11ef-9b9d-75eda371a206/file-jaoe38c1ly9ttyes.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"AP EAPCET 2021 - 20th August Morning Shift Chemistry - General Organic Chemistry Question 18 English Explanation\"></p>\n<p>The most reactive towards electrophilic reagent is $$o$$-cresol.</p>\n<p>The phenolic $$(-\\mathrm{OH})$$ group increases the electron density on benzene ring through resonance. With increase in electron density, the reactivity towards electrophilic reagent increases. The decreasing order of activating influence of substituents towards electrophilic reagent is</p>\n<p>$$\\begin{aligned}\n&amp; \\mathrm{NR}_2&gt;-\\mathrm{NH} R&gt;-\\mathrm{NH}_2&gt;-\\mathrm{OH}&gt;-\\mathrm{OR}&gt; \\\\\n&amp; -\\mathrm{NHCOR}&gt;-\\mathrm{ph}&gt;-R\n\\end{aligned}$$</p>",
